1.
    a.
        Cardiomyopathy can cause heart failure because the walls of the heart have become stretched, thickened, or stiff. This inhibits the regular rhythm of contraction of the heart which is required to pump blood around, or may cause the walls of the heart to become damaged in that process.
    b?
        The atria are the chambers of the heart which receive blood from the veins and pump that blood into the ventricles. The left atrium receives blood from the pulmonary vein, and the right atrium receives blood from the vena cava and pumps blood into the right ventricle.
    c.
        Blood in the pulmonary artery is deoxygenated and does not have a lot of oxygen; blood in the aorta is rich in oxygen as it has passed through the lungs.
    d.
        A heart-lung bypass machine keeps the patient alive by acting as a pump and as a lung by keeping blood circulating in the patient, as well as oxygenating the blood as it pumps it and removes oxygen, replacing the functionality of the heart and the lungs. The patient cannot live if he does not have oxygenated blood moving through his arteries, so this is why it is used.
    e.
        The patient needs to be given immunosuppressants as the new heart will not have the exact same antigens, so otherwise will be treated as a pathogen and attacked by the patient's immune response. Immunosuppressants suppress the immune system, reducing immune response and reducing the amount of damage to the new heart so it can function properly.
    f?
        Patients should not smoke after their heart transplants because smoking irritates the heart and causes build-up of cholesterol, which may cause the transplant to fail or may cause the cholesterol to build up and another heart attack to happen
    g.
        A diet with appropriate (not too much but not too little) proportions of micro- and macro-nutrients such as carbohydrates, protein, fiber, vitamins etc
    h.
        200 * 75% = 150 people
    i.
        Because strenuous activities would require more oxygen and would require the heart to beat faster and with more force, which might stress the heart and cause the transplant to fail
    j.
        Because they will have to take immunosuppressants, which indiscriminately suppresses the immune system, so the immune system will be less able to fend off and prevent from multiplying small amounts of bacteria in food, and so the patient will be more susceptible to food poisoning.
