    a.
        i.
            With the nucleus removed
        ii?
            The single cell divides by mitosis several times to develop into an embryo
    b.
        Although there were more successful pregnancies using adult body cells, the there were less offspring produced, suggesting a high rate of miscarriage. In addition, those offspring were short-lived, suggesting that adult body cells do not produce healthy foetuses/babies. In addition, more surrogates were used for adult body cells (twice as many), so relatively there were less offspring produced (2/2 = 1 vs 2/1 = 2) for adult body cells, though there are still relatively more successful pregnancies. This, though, still leads to the conclusion that there is a high rate of miscarriages. Hence, fetus body cells is more successful in cloning monkeys, because they produce healthier babies with less chance of miscarriage and the babies are not short-lived.
5.
    Using a bomb calorimeter, place 1g of crushed potato chips of the first type in the chamber. Measure the temperature of the water, and then (supplying oxygen etc) ignite the potato chip. Measure continuously the temperature of the water, and take the peak temperature, and subtract from that the starting temperature. Repeat this three times and take the average of those repetitions. Then, repeat all of this with the second type of chip. Whichever chip has the lowest average temperature increase contains the least energy.
6.
    a.
        Create a coordinate-system for each field. Then, use a random number generator to generate a coordinate. Use quadrats: place a quadrat at that coordinate and count the number of each plant in that quadrat.
    b.
        i.
            (7+3+2+1+2)/5 = 15/5 = 3
        ii.
            quadrat is 0.25m^2, so 3 * 4 = 12 dandelions per m^2
    c.
        There are more numbers of all species in field A than in field B. Furthermore, in field B, there are some species which are simply not present. However, the maximum number of plants per quadrat is the same in both fields (7), which is much higher than the rest in field B, suggesting clumps of dandelions. It seems overall that violets, heathers, and buttercups are do not fare well in these fields when compared to dandelions, as dandelions in both fields are much more numerous.
    d?
        The students could attempt to plant buttercups in a waterlogged environment as well as dandelions. If only the dandelions thrive, then this is possibly a factor. The students could also attempt to waterlog a portion of field A where there are buttercups, or attempt to plant buttercups in a waterlogged portion of field A. If the buttercupts do not thrive, then this is possibly a factor. The students could also install water drainage in field B. If buttercups appear (planting may be necessary to accelerate the process), then this is possibly a factor. Finally, the students should measure the water content in the soil of field B. If it is relatively dry (in relation to field A), and is not excessively wet, then this is likely not the reason.
7.
    a.
        Cell differentiation is important as the body contains many specialised cells, and for them to develop from a single fertilized egg cell, it must be able to differentiate into those specialised cells, which are vital for life (red blood cells for carrying oxygen e.g.)
    b.
        i.
            D
        ii.
            Adult stem cells cannot become all cell types, so may not be suitable for certain diseases. In addition, adult stem cells may be rejected by the patient. In contrast, embryonic stem cells are cloned from the patient so will not be rejected, and can become all cell types, but there are ethical concerns about cloning and creating an embryo just for medical treatment.